.TH getbar 1 "@PROJECT_YEAR@" "@PROJECT_VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
getbar \- HTTP download throughput bar series
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B getbar
.RI [ OPTION ]...
.IR URL
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B getbar
downloads
.IR URL
with HTTP or HTTPS GET using libcurl and records a bar series on standard output.
Use block mode to record per-block receive durations in microseconds, or interval
mode to record bytes received per time slice.
.PP
By default the full timeline is recorded, including connection and server delay
(TTFB in block mode, leading zero intervals in interval mode). Polynomial
.BR \-p
offset is zero unless
.B \-d
is set.
.PP
With
.BR \-d ", pre-data wait is omitted from the bar series, "
.BR \-w ", "
.BR \-c ", and the polynomial fit; "
.BR \-p
offset then reports the stripped delay (seconds in interval mode, preamble bar
count in block mode).
.PP
End of output means the download completed, hit
.B \-\-window
or
.BR \-\-size-max ,
or failed.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-b ", " \-\-block-size =\fINUM\fR[kmgKMG]
Split the download into blocks of
.IR NUM
bytes and record each block duration in microseconds.
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-interval =\fINUM\fR[um][s]
Record bytes received every
.IR NUM
microseconds, milliseconds, or seconds.
.IR NUM
may be fractional (for example
.BR 0.1s
or
.BR 100.5ms ).
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-size-max =\fINUM\fR[kmgKMG]
Stop after receiving
.IR NUM
bytes.
.TP
.BR \-w ", " \-\-window =\fINUM\fR[um][s]
Stop after the given time limit. With
.BR \-d ,
the limit applies only after data starts arriving.
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-polynomial =\fIORDER\fR
After the series, print a polynomial fit line:
.IR offset
followed by coefficients. By default offset is zero; with
.BR \-d ,
offset is the stripped pre-data delay (seconds in interval mode, preamble bar
count in block mode). The same fit is drawn on the
.BR \-\-gnuplot
chart when this option is given.
.TP
.BR \-g ", " \-\-gnuplot =\fIFILE\fR
Write gnuplot output to
.IR FILE .
Image extensions
.RB ( .png ", " .svg ", " .pdf ", " .eps )
are rendered with gnuplot; any other extension saves a gnuplot script without
rendering (gnuplot is not required in that case).
If
.BR \-\-polynomial
is also set, include the fitted curve in the plot.
Optional theming is read from
.IR $XDG_CONFIG_HOME /getbar/gnuplot.rc
when present.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-force
Overwrite an existing gnuplot output file.
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-estimate-bps =\fINUM\fR[um][s]
After the series, print an estimated download speed in bytes per second measured
from
.IR NUM
after data starts arriving until the transfer ends.
.TP
.BR \-c ", " \-\-count
After the series, print one summary line:
.IR series-count size-bytes duration-usec bytes-per-second .
.IR series-count
is the number of bar values;
.IR size-bytes
is total bytes received;
.IR duration-usec
is wall-clock transfer time from the measurement origin to finish (from
connection start unless
.B \-d
is set);
.IR bytes-per-second
is average throughput over that duration.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-delay-started
Omit pre-data wait from the bar series and from
.BR \-w ", " \-c ", and the polynomial fit. "
.BR \-p
offset reports the stripped delay.
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Do not print the bar series.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Log transfer details to standard error.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print help and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print version and exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic measurements
.TP
64 KiB blocks:
.B getbar \-b 64k https://example.com/file
.TP
100 ms intervals with speed estimate after 1 s (series hidden):
.B getbar \-i 100ms \-e 1s \-q https://example.com/file
.TP
Summary line after interval series:
.B getbar \-i 100ms \-c https://example.com/file
.br
Output ends with a line such as
.IR "20 1048576 1523400 688421"
(number of bars, bytes, microseconds, B/s).
.TP
Print time-to-first-byte (microseconds) from block mode:
.B getbar \-b 64k \-s 256k https://example.com/file | awk '{print $1}'
.SS Controlled size or duration
.TP
Sample 10 MiB and print steady-state B/s estimate:
.B getbar \-i 100ms \-s 10M \-e 2s \-q https://mirror.example/file
.TP
Run at most 30 s (soak test):
.B getbar \-i 1s \-w 30s \-v https://cdn.example/large.bin
.TP
Stop at whichever comes first, 50 MiB or 60 s:
.B getbar \-b 1M \-s 50M \-w 60s https://example.com/file
.SS Charts and analysis
.TP
Fractional interval, 3 s window, verbose, chart overwrite:
.B getbar \-vfw3 \-i0.1s \-g /tmp/getbar.png \-f https://example.com/file
.TP
Block chart with quadratic polynomial overlay:
.B getbar \-b 64k \-p 2 \-g /tmp/getbar.png https://example.com/file
.TP
Interval chart with polynomial overlay:
.B getbar \-i 100ms \-p 2 \-g chart.png \-f https://example.com/file
.TP
Export SVG for reports:
.B getbar \-i 200ms \-p 2 \-g report.svg \-f https://example.com/file
.TP
Save a gnuplot script instead of rendering:
.B getbar \-b 64k \-g /tmp/getbar.gp https://example.com/file
.SS Comparing mirrors
.TP
One estimated B/s line per URL (5 MiB sample):
.B for url in https://mirror-a.example/file https://mirror-b.example/file; do printf '%s\\t' "$url"; getbar \-i 100ms \-s 5M \-e 1s \-q "$url"; done
.TP
Sort mirrors by estimated throughput (\fImirrors.txt\fR lists one URL per line):
.B while read \-r url; do bps=$(getbar \-i 100ms \-s 5M \-e 1s \-q "$url") || continue; printf '%s\\t%s\\n' "$bps" "$url"; done < mirrors.txt | sort \-nr
.SS Shell integration
.TP
Verbose logs on stderr, series on stdout:
.B getbar \-v \-i 100ms \-s 10M https://example.com/file > series.txt
.TP
Save series and chart in one run:
.B getbar \-i 100ms \-s 20M \-g run.png \-f https://example.com/file | tee series.txt
.TP
Rough MiB/s from the estimate line:
.B bps=$(getbar \-i 100ms \-s 10M \-e 1s \-q https://example.com/file); awk \-v b="$bps" 'BEGIN { printf "~ %.2f MiB/s\\n", b / 1024 / 1024 }'
.SH FILES
.TP
.I $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/getbar/gnuplot.rc
Optional gnuplot commands loaded before plotting (colors, fonts, grid, and so on).
.SH AUTHOR
Written by @PROJECT_AUTHOR@ <@PROJECT_EMAIL@>.
